    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#dthorn-thorn2009"/>, p. <citedRange>118</citedRange> (no image)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>122800</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Πολυάρατος">Πολυάρατ<supplied reason="lost">ος</supplied></name></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Polyaratos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Polyaratos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Polyaratos.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>The Thorns only give a description of the place and a diplomatic transcription of the preserved letters, with a suggestion about the date.</p>
	           <p>Names cut on sarcophagi are either at the nominative case, as a caption, or at the genitive, as owner's marks. So we might also have here a genitive,
	           which would not be dialectal, ending in <foreign xml:lang="grc">-ου</foreign>.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
